        <h1 class="display">How to start a grassroots football club in 2026.</h1>
        <p class="blog-post__lede">
          The practical, in-order guide to getting a grassroots football club off the ground in 2026: legal structure, FA affiliation, safeguarding, pitches, players, kit, and the operational systems that decide whether your club survives its third year. Written by someone who co-founded one and is still running it.
        </p>
      </header>

      <AuthorByline publishDate={publishDate} updateDate={updateDate} readTime="17 min read" />

      <section class="blog-post__body">

        <p>Most grassroots football clubs that get started in the UK fold inside three years. Not because nobody wants to play, and not because there isn't demand. The demand is there. Local FAs across England are actively short of affiliated clubs, especially in girls', women's, and disability football. The problem is that running a club turns out to be 70% paperwork, scheduling, and chasing parents for kit fees, and 30% football. Most volunteers sign up for the football and quietly burn out on the paperwork.</p>

        <p>This post is the guide I would have wanted three years ago when I co-founded HVV Football Factory in The Hague. It walks through the full sequence of starting a club in the UK in 2026: the legal structure, FA affiliation, the safeguarding requirements that changed for the 2026/2027 season, finding a pitch, recruiting players, kit and equipment, and the operational systems that decide whether your club is still running in 2029. The focus is England specifically because the affiliation process is most clearly documented there. Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland, and most European countries have parallel systems which I touch on briefly.</p>

        <h2>The short version</h2>
        <p>If you only have five minutes, here is the in-order checklist:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Decide what kind of club you are building (age group, format, ambition).</li>
          <li>Find your founding committee. Minimum three people. Manager, Secretary, Treasurer.</li>
          <li>Write a constitution and open a club bank account.</li>
          <li>Recruit a Club Welfare Officer (DBS-checked, FA-trained). This is now mandatory and the most common reason affiliations get delayed.</li>
          <li>Affiliate to your County FA. Costs around £80 per season. Affiliation opens in June.</li>
          <li>Register with a league for competitive fixtures (around £88 per season).</li>
          <li>Sort Public Liability Insurance. Required for affiliation.</li>
          <li>Find a pitch. Usually the largest single expense.</li>
          <li>Order kit and equipment.</li>
          <li>Recruit players through schools, Facebook groups, and grassroots directories.</li>
          <li>Set up the operational systems (training schedules, kit tracking, communication, payments) before you have 50 children showing up on a Saturday morning.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The thing nobody tells you is that step 11 is what kills clubs. Steps 1 through 10 are admin-heavy but finite. Step 11 is the ongoing weekly load that wears volunteers down. Plan for that from day one and your club has a fighting chance.</p>

        <h2>Step 1: Decide what you are actually building</h2>
        <p>Clubs that fail tend to fail because they did not pick a lane. They try to be a youth club, a women's club, and a Sunday League side at the same time, and end up under-serving all three.</p>
        <p>The first decision is identity:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Who is this for?</strong> Youth (U6 to U18), adult open-age, women's, walking football, disability football, a mix.</li>
          <li><strong>What level?</strong> Sunday League for fun, county league with ambition, FA Charter Standard pathway for youth, semi-professional aspirations.</li>
          <li><strong>What does success look like in three years?</strong> One team that survives, four teams that thrive, promotion through the pyramid, fielding a women's first team.</li>
          <li><strong>Why does this club need to exist?</strong> Is there a gap in your local area? Are existing clubs full? Are you trying to be different in some specific way?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>At HVV Football Factory we were clear from the start: a grassroots club focused on inclusive youth football and adult recreational teams, not a competitive pathway, not a feeder for academies, just a place where local kids and adults could play. Being clear about that meant we said no to a lot of opportunities (academy partnerships, talent ID schemes, semi-pro ambitions) and got better at the thing we picked.</p>
        <p>Write down your identity in two or three sentences. Show it to your founding committee. If anyone disagrees, fix it now. Disagreements about what a club is for at year three are much worse than at year zero.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Find your founding committee</h2>
        <p>The absolute minimum is three people, covering three roles. In real grassroots clubs, the same person often holds two of these for the first year.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chair (or Manager):</strong> The person who runs committee meetings, makes the final call on disagreements, and is the public face of the club.</li>
          <li><strong>Secretary:</strong> The admin engine. Handles FA affiliation, league registration, fixture coordination, communication with parents, minutes from meetings. By far the heaviest workload.</li>
          <li><strong>Treasurer:</strong> Bank account, fees collection, expenses, end-of-year accounts. Lighter time commitment than secretary but higher consequence if it goes wrong.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>You also need a Club Welfare Officer (more on this in Step 4) but this is a separate role from the three above, and ideally a separate person.</p>
        <p>The committee is everything. Pick people who genuinely have 4-8 hours a week to give, and who will still be around in three years. A founding committee made up of parents whose kids will age out of the U10s in two seasons is a committee that vanishes when those kids move on.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Legal structure</h2>
        <p>Most small new clubs start as an unincorporated members' association. No Companies House filing, no annual accounts, just a written constitution and a club bank account. It is the simplest possible structure and works for the first 1-2 seasons.</p>
        <p>Once you start handling grant money, owning equipment, leasing a pitch, or signing employment contracts (for paid coaches), you should upgrade to one of:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Community Amateur Sports Club (CASC).</strong> Tax reliefs on income, business rates, and donations. Roughly two-thirds of registered grassroots clubs end up as CASC eventually. Annual filing requirements are light.</li>
          <li><strong>Community Interest Company (CIC).</strong> Limited liability for committee members. Asset lock so the club cannot be sold off for personal profit. Better positioning for Football Foundation capital grants. Slightly more annual paperwork than CASC.</li>
          <li><strong>Registered Charity.</strong> Maximum tax benefits but the heaviest governance burden. Usually only worth it for multi-team clubs with significant facilities or community programming.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For your founding year, start as an unincorporated members' association with a written constitution. Open a club bank account at any UK high street bank in the club's name (Lloyds, Barclays, and HSBC all do this; some online-only banks like Starling have club account products). Most banks ask for the constitution plus identification for at least two committee members.</p>
        <p>Write the constitution properly. Use the FA's template (Google "FA model constitution grassroots") as a starting point. Read through it. Change the placeholders. Get the committee to sign it. Keep a copy. You will need it for FA affiliation and any grant application.</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Safeguarding and the Welfare Officer</h2>
        <p>This is the single most common reason new club affiliations get delayed in 2026/2027. The FA has tightened safeguarding requirements meaningfully:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Club Welfare Officer required.</strong> Every affiliated club must have a named Welfare Officer who is DBS-checked and has completed the FA Welfare Officer training.</li>
          <li><strong>Player Welfare Course for all team officials.</strong> Every named manager, coach, and assistant attached to an open-aged team must complete the Player Welfare Course as part of affiliation. This was new for 2024/2025 and is now standard.</li>
          <li><strong>Safeguarding Declaration.</strong> Mandatory for the 2026/2027 affiliation season. Every club accepts a declaration that they understand and will adhere to safeguarding responsibilities.</li>
          <li><strong>Welfare Officer for adult teams.</strong> Clubs with adult teams require a named Welfare Officer (Adult Teams) who has completed the Player Welfare Course.</li>
          <li><strong>DBS checks.</strong> Any adult team with 16/17-year-old players requires all named team officials to hold a completed in-date FA DBS.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The practical implication: identify your Welfare Officer at the same time as your founding committee. They need to complete the DBS process (which takes 4-8 weeks) and the FA Welfare Officer training (online, 2-3 hours). Start this in March or April if you want to be affiliated by August.</p>
        <p>Two pieces of advice. First, do not appoint someone to Welfare Officer as a token role. The Welfare Officer is the safeguarding lead. They need to actually do the role, including being the point of contact if anything goes wrong. Second, do not have the Welfare Officer also be the Chair or Manager. The independence matters.</p>

        <h2>Step 5: County FA affiliation</h2>
        <p>This is the step that legally registers your club as a football club in the eyes of the FA. Without it, you cannot play affiliated fixtures, you cannot get insurance through the FA's scheme, and you cannot apply for FA-administered grants.</p>
        <p>Affiliation runs through your County FA. There are 50 County FAs in England, organised geographically. Find yours (Google "[your county] FA"). Affiliation typically opens in June each year for the season that starts in August.</p>
        <p>The process is online, through the FA Clubs Portal. You will need:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your club's constitution</li>
          <li>Named committee members (Chair, Secretary, Treasurer, Welfare Officer)</li>
          <li>Named team managers and coaches with their DBS and Player Welfare Course completion</li>
          <li>Public Liability Insurance certificate</li>
          <li>Your main home ground (a pitch you have hire agreement with, even informally)</li>
          <li>The team(s) you are affiliating, with format (11-a-side, 9-a-side, 7-a-side, 5-a-side), age group, and proposed league</li>
          <li>Payment of the affiliation fee (varies by County FA, typically £60-£100 per season)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The affiliation fee depends on number of teams. A single-team club affiliating one open-age men's team will pay around £80 per season. A multi-team youth club affiliating six youth teams pays more, but with discounts per additional team.</p>
        <p>What tends to go wrong: paperwork submitted with missing fields (especially DBS not yet processed for one coach, holding up the entire affiliation). Submit early. June is calmer than August at the County FA office.</p>

        <h2>Step 6: League registration</h2>
        <p>Affiliation tells the FA you exist. League registration is what lets you actually play competitive fixtures.</p>
        <p>Once affiliated, you contact the league(s) you want to play in. Most leagues run their own application process which typically includes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>An application form with team details</li>
          <li>League registration fee (typically £80-£100 per season per team)</li>
          <li>A deposit (refundable at end of season if you do not have outstanding fines or disputes)</li>
          <li>Commitment to fielding teams for every fixture (failure to fulfil fixtures attracts fines)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Use the FA's <strong>Find a League</strong> tool (on the County FA website) to identify leagues in your area at your level. Most areas have a county league, district leagues, and sometimes specialist leagues (Sunday League, Saturday League, youth pyramid).</p>
        <p>Apply to multiple leagues if your area has them. Some leagues fill quickly, others are short of teams. Get a confirmation in writing of your league acceptance before you commit to fixture dates.</p>

        <h2>Step 7: Insurance</h2>
        <p>Public Liability Insurance is required for affiliation. Personal Accident Insurance for players is required by most leagues.</p>
        <p>Two routes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>The FA's affiliated insurance scheme.</strong> Bundled at affiliation time, covers Public Liability and other club exposures. Convenient and good value for the basic policy. The FA partners with specific brokers who change occasionally.</li>
          <li><strong>Direct from a specialist sports insurer.</strong> Sporting Risk, Marsh Sport, and Allianz all offer grassroots-specific products. Worth a quote if your club is larger or has unusual risk (own ground, paid staff, larger equipment value).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For a first-year single-team club, the FA scheme is usually the right answer.</p>

        <h2>Step 8: Find a pitch</h2>
        <p>This is the most expensive line item in a grassroots club's budget. A reasonable rule of thumb: pitch hire alone costs £40-£80 per session for a community 3G or grass pitch, and clubs need at least one weekly training slot plus a fortnightly home match slot during the season. That puts pitch hire at £2,000-£4,000 per year for a single team.</p>
        <p>Where to look:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Football Foundation PitchFinder.</strong> National directory of pitches with availability and contact details. Search by postcode.</li>
          <li><strong>Local authority leisure services.</strong> Most councils run a sports facilities booking system. Council pitches are usually the cheapest option but often the most worn-down.</li>
          <li><strong>Schools and colleges.</strong> Many school pitches are available for hire outside school hours. Sixth form colleges and private schools often have well-maintained pitches and willing community use schemes.</li>
          <li><strong>Other clubs.</strong> Sometimes another club has more pitch time than they need and is willing to share. Worth asking around at the County FA office.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What to negotiate: long-term commitment in exchange for better rate. A council pitch booked for one Saturday is one price. Booked for every Saturday and Tuesday for a whole season is often 20-30% cheaper per session because the council values the predictability.</p>
        <p>What to verify: the pitch is approved for affiliated fixtures (some pitches are not), drainage works (some pitches are unplayable from October to March), changing facilities exist if your league requires them, and you have a written letter of permission you can submit to the FA.</p>

        <h2>Step 9: Kit and equipment</h2>
        <p>This is the area I know best. The short version: budget about £30 per player for entry-level kit, £45-£60 per player for mid-tier brand kit. Plus goalkeeper kit, match balls, training balls, bibs, cones, first aid, kit bag, and a pump. A single-team launch budget is usually £500-£800 just for kit and equipment.</p>
        <p>I wrote a separate post on <a href="/blog/football-kit-ordering-guide-grassroots/">how to order kit for grassroots clubs in 2026</a> which goes into supplier comparison, pricing, lead times, and the classic ordering mistakes. The key things to know:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Order in May or June for an August/September season start. Lead times are 3-6 weeks at peak.</li>
          <li>Spend less on shirts, more on goalkeeper kit (it takes more punishment).</li>
          <li>Buy 15-20% over what you think you need (player turnover, replacements).</li>
          <li>Get the sizing right with an in-person session for youth teams.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Equipment for a single team typically includes: 4-6 match balls, 8-12 training balls, two sets of bibs in different colours, 20-30 cones, agility ladders, a first aid kit, a kit bag, a ball pump, training poles, and goalkeeper gloves. Total cost for that set of equipment is around £200-£350. The Football Foundation's Grow the Game programme includes a £350 Nike kit and equipment voucher for new teams, which covers this if you qualify.</p>

        <h2>Step 10: Recruit players</h2>
        <p>Most new clubs overestimate how hard recruitment is. A clear pitch in the right places fills a team faster than you expect.</p>
        <p>What works:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Local schools.</strong> Laminated A4 posters on school gates and an ask to PE teachers to mention it. Especially effective for youth clubs.</li>
          <li><strong>Facebook community groups.</strong> Every town has a "[Town name] Local" group with 5,000-30,000 members. One clear post, pinned for a week, generates more interest than weeks of word-of-mouth.</li>
          <li><strong>Grassroots directories.</strong> List your club on the main UK directories (PlayFootball.fa.com, England Football, Junior Grassroots Hub) so parents searching Google find you.</li>
          <li><strong>Existing community connections.</strong> Talk to local primary schools, churches, youth groups, scout troops. Especially for youth and inclusion-focused clubs.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What does not work as well as you would expect: paid advertising, glossy launch events, and trying to fill every age group at once.</p>
        <p>A new club is better off starting with one or two strong teams in popular age groups (U10 and U12 are easiest to fill in youth, open-age in adult) and adding more as you grow. Better to have one full U10 squad than three half-full age groups that all need cancelling because you cannot get eleven players to a match.</p>

        <h2>Step 11: The operational systems</h2>
        <p>Here is the part that decides whether you are still running in three years.</p>
        <p>Once steps 1-10 are done, you have a club. Affiliated, insured, with a pitch, kit, and players. The football starts. And so does the constant operational load:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Fixture scheduling and communication</li>
          <li>Subs collection (weekly or monthly)</li>
          <li>Match day organisation (who is playing, who is bringing what)</li>
          <li>Equipment management (who has the balls, who has the bibs, who has the kit)</li>
          <li>Coach availability tracking</li>
          <li>Parent communication for youth teams</li>
          <li>Disciplinary records (yellow and red cards, FA reporting)</li>
          <li>Safeguarding incident logs</li>
          <li>End-of-season audit, accounts, and grant applications</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is what burns out volunteers. The secretary who gets 47 WhatsApp messages a week from parents. The treasurer chasing subs in arrears. The kit man who genuinely cannot find six of last year's training balls.</p>
        <p>The clubs that survive year three have one thing in common: they set up systems for these tasks before they became urgent. Specifically:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Communication: Spond, TeamSnap, or LoveAdmin.</strong> One tool that handles fixtures, RSVPs, and parent communication. The default is Spond and it is free.</li>
          <li><strong>Payments: Spond Pay, GoCardless, or direct debit through your bank.</strong> Automate subs so you are not chasing parents on WhatsApp every week.</li>
          <li><strong>Equipment tracking: ClubShed, a maintained spreadsheet, or a paper kit cupboard ledger.</strong> Track what you own as you use it. The number-one operational expense at every grassroots club is equipment that gets lost because nobody tracked it. We wrote a <a href="/blog/grassroots-football-equipment-guide/">full guide on equipment management for grassroots clubs</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Accounts: a simple spreadsheet or Xero/QuickBooks.</strong> Whatever you pick, do it monthly, not as a year-end panic.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Pick tools and processes that fit your committee's actual habits, not the ones you wish they had. A volunteer secretary who lives in WhatsApp will not switch to Microsoft Teams. A treasurer who is comfortable in a spreadsheet does not need accounting software in year one.</p>
        <p>The trap is trying to do this without any systems and assuming "we'll just be organised." Every grassroots club thinks this in year one. By year three, the volunteers who said it have rage-quit, and a club that should be three teams is back to one.</p>

        <h2>Funding the launch</h2>
        <p>Realistic launch budget for a single-team affiliated grassroots club in 2026:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>FA affiliation: £80</li>
          <li>League registration: £88</li>
          <li>Insurance (FA scheme): around £150 for a single team's basic cover</li>
          <li>Pitch hire (1 training + 1 home fixture every 2 weeks, season): £2,000-£3,000</li>
          <li>Kit (16-player squad, entry-level): £500-£800</li>
          <li>Equipment (balls, bibs, cones, first aid, kit bag): £250-£400</li>
          <li>Welfare Officer DBS and training: included in FA process, around £20 DBS fee</li>
          <li>Constitution and admin: minimal</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Total Year 1 cost: £3,000-£4,500 for a single team.</strong></p>
        <p>Funding sources:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Player subs.</strong> Most clubs charge £80-£150 per player per season for adults, £150-£400 per player per season for youth. A 16-player squad at £200 per player covers £3,200, which is most of the launch budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Football Foundation Grow the Game.</strong> £350 Nike kit voucher for new teams, plus affiliation and pitch hire support for the first year. Apply in the season before you launch.</li>
          <li><strong>County FA grants.</strong> Small grants for new teams, varies by county.</li>
          <li><strong>Local sponsorship.</strong> A local business name on your shirt for £200-£500 a year is genuinely achievable. Worth asking your local pub, takeaway, or estate agent.</li>
          <li><strong>Awards for All (National Lottery Community Fund).</strong> £300-£20,000 for community projects. Clubs framing themselves as community participation projects regularly succeed here.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The <a href="/blog/football-foundation-grants-equipment-grassroots/">Football Foundation grants guide</a> covers the application process in detail. For a brand new club, Grow the Game is the most realistic first grant. Apply early; processing takes 4-6 weeks.</p>

        <h2>Beyond England: brief regional notes</h2>
        <p><strong>Wales:</strong> Affiliation runs through the Football Association of Wales. Grants come from the Cymru Football Foundation. Similar process to England but smaller scale.</p>
        <p><strong>Scotland:</strong> Scottish FA handles affiliation. Sportscotland and the Cashback for Communities programme fund participation. Slightly heavier emphasis on community impact in grant applications.</p>
        <p><strong>Northern Ireland:</strong> The Irish Football Association runs affiliation. The Step into Football programme provides start-up support for new clubs.</p>
        <p><strong>Republic of Ireland:</strong> Football Association of Ireland affiliation. The FAI's Football for All programme and Sport Ireland's grants cover most funding needs.</p>
        <p><strong>Continental Europe:</strong> Mostly regional. Each country has its own federation (DFB in Germany, KNVB in Netherlands, RFEF in Spain, FFF in France) and most grassroots support comes from regional sports federations or municipal sports councils. UEFA's HatTrick programme funds national federations rather than individual clubs directly. The principles are the same (formal affiliation, safeguarding requirements, pitch hire, kit, recruitment), but the specific bodies and grant programmes differ.</p>

        <h2>What I learned from co-founding HVV Football Factory</h2>
        <p>A few things that are not in any FA documentation but matter more than most of what is:</p>
        <p><strong>The committee picks the club's ceiling.</strong> A founding committee of two parents whose kids will move on in three years is a club with a three-year ceiling. Recruit committee members whose investment is in the club itself, not just in their own child's pathway.</p>
        <p><strong>Operational systems matter more than match results.</strong> Clubs that lose 8-0 every week but pay subs on time, train weekly, and turn up to every fixture survive. Clubs that win their first season but cannot organise themselves do not.</p>
        <p><strong>Track equipment from day one.</strong> The cost of letting equipment drift for one season is about €1,000 in replacements per team per year. Replacing the same kit twice is a real budget line. Track it from the start.</p>
        <p><strong>Be honest about what you are.</strong> Grassroots football is not a pathway to professional football for most players. Pretending otherwise sets parents up for disappointment and burns out coaches. Be honest about being a community club with the football as the centre, not the only point.</p>
        <p><strong>Plan your succession from year one.</strong> Whoever founds the club should be planning their replacement on the committee within 3-4 years. Clubs that survive are clubs that have plans for the founder leaving.</p>

        <h2>A practical month-by-month plan for launching</h2>
        <p>If you want to start a club for the 2027/2028 season starting in August 2027, here is the rough timeline:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>December 2026:</strong> Initial conversations. Identify potential committee members. Discuss identity and ambition.</li>
          <li><strong>January 2027:</strong> Founding meeting. Agree constitution. Identify Welfare Officer. Open bank account.</li>
          <li><strong>February 2027:</strong> Welfare Officer starts DBS and Welfare Officer course. Coach DBS processes begin.</li>
          <li><strong>March 2027:</strong> Pitch search. Approach 3-5 venues for pricing and availability.</li>
          <li><strong>April 2027:</strong> Confirm pitch. Confirm coaches with completed DBS. Start Grow the Game application if eligible.</li>
          <li><strong>May 2027:</strong> Order kit. Set up Spond or equivalent for communication. Set up ClubShed or equivalent for equipment tracking.</li>
          <li><strong>June 2027:</strong> Affiliation opens. Submit FA affiliation. Submit league registration. Confirm insurance.</li>
          <li><strong>July 2027:</strong> Pre-season training. Final equipment ordering. Test communication systems.</li>
          <li><strong>August 2027:</strong> Season starts.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>This is 8 months of preparation. You can do it in 4 if you have to. You cannot do it in 4 weeks and have it work.</p>

        <h2>Why ClubShed exists in this context</h2>
        <p>I co-founded HVV Football Factory because I wanted to play football in a club where the organisation did not actively get in the way of the football. After three seasons, I built ClubShed because the single biggest operational problem we had not solved was equipment management. Footballs went missing. Bibs vanished. Kit was kept by players who left. The committee replaced the same gear every season because nobody could answer the question "what do we actually own right now."</p>
        <p>ClubShed is a grassroots equipment tracker built specifically for that problem. Track every item by photo and QR code. Coaches check items in and out with one tap. Condition is graded over seasons. At the end of the year, you generate a one-click PDF audit report that goes straight into your grant application or your committee accounts.</p>
        <p>Free for one team, 30 items, and 3 coaches. €15.99 a month for unlimited teams, items, and coaches when you outgrow that. No card required to start.</p>
        <p>Starting a club is a big project. Most of the work in the first year is paperwork and process. We cannot make the FA affiliation faster, but we can take the equipment tracking problem off your plate so that when you reach year three, you still have your committee and your sanity.</p>

